<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / CBI finds gloom across Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON is not the only European capital suffering from a recession, the
Confederation of British Industry said yesterday after carrying out the
first pan-European business survey published since sterling's withdrawal
from the exchange rate mechanism on September 16.
The CBI's survey covered 2,500 companies in five European capitals and found
that confidence is low in London, Brussels, Paris and Rome, with gloom
spread across sectors. Activity in retailing, hotels, tourism and
construction has fallen, the CBI said.
According to the CBI, business optimism among manufacturers in the four
cities is also down. All are looking to reduce further their manufacturing
labour forces over the next six months. Madrid is the only centre expecting
a more encouraging outlook.
The survey suggests that manufacturing output and investment levels in
London may rise marginally, while production elsewhere is expected to
decline. Optimism in the banking and finance sector was generally lower in
the face of the continuing uncertainty surrounding the currency and equity
markets.
Construction appears to be the universal blackspot, with none of the cities
suggesting that an improvement in activity is likely. Optimism and
investment programmes remain at low levels.
The retail sector appears universally gloomy, with cons-umer confidence low
and staffing levels falling. London retailers say they are still affected by
consumer preference for paying off debt, while the downturn in the French
economy is now hitting retail spending in Paris.
European Capitals' State of Trade. CBI, 103 New Oxford St, WC1A 1DU. Free.
</TEXT>
