<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / More women graduates find work than men
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of female graduates finding work within six months of graduation
exceeded the number of males for the first time last year.
Figures compiled by the Central Services Unit for Graduate Employment and
the Association of Graduate Careers Advisory Services show that although
women made up less than half the 135,000 graduates in the study, 31,359
women had found permanent or short-term work in the UK or overseas by
December last year compared with 31,273 men.
A 5.5 per cent increase in the total of graduates combined with a depressed
labour market left 11.5 per cent of graduates still unoccupied after six
months, up from 8.1 per cent in 1990.
The jobless rate for women graduates was 9.4 per cent and 13.4 per cent for
men.
Teacher training rose in popularity, with more than 5,000 graduates, 4.5 per
cent of the total, choosing it last year compared with 3.7 per cent in 1990.
Women continue to outnumber men in teacher training by more than two to one.
The figures were drawn from surveys carried out by universities,
polytechnics and colleges.
</TEXT>
