<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Upward trend of sales in north is reversed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARP downturn in sales and confidence in northern England was reported
yesterday. Liverpool chamber of commerce, covering Merseyside, west Cheshire
and north Wales, reported a reversal between July and September of all
upward trends in home and export deliveries and orders.
Steep job losses are forecast for this quarter, with 29 per cent planning to
shed labour. That follows four successive quarters in which the trend of job
losses had stabilised. This quarter's plunge is forecast at a similar scale
to two years ago, when 35 per cent of companies in the Liverpool survey cut
jobs in the fourth quarter.
The pattern is similar to larger surveys by the Manchester-centred
north-west chambers and the Leeds-collated chambers for Yorkshire and
Humberside. The only indicator not in negative balance - more companies
reporting a decrease than an increase - is for export orders, but even here
the figure is zero after being positive last year. The Hotpoint washing
machine factory at Llandudno Junction, north Wales, is to close with the
loss of 100 jobs.
</TEXT>
