<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Race for the White House: Central policies of the contenders
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
GEORGE BUSH
Defence: Proposes real 4 per cent decline in defence budget 1993-97, with
steady reductions in troop levels to 'base force' with 12 active army
divisions, 12 carrier battle groups and 15.25 fighter wing equivalents.
Seeks 150,000 troops in Europe. Wants to kill off Seawolf submarine, Osprey
aircraft. Backs development of GPALS anti-missile defences.
Abortion: Would ban abortion except in cases of rape, incest or threat to
woman's life. Has repeatedly vetoed bills including federal funding for
abortions or abortion counselling.
Environment: Helped enact Clean Air Act but has held up some rules
implementing act. Wants more attention paid to economic cost of
environmental protection.
Healthcare: Proposes tax credits worth dollars 1,250 per person to help
cover most of those without health insurance. Seeks reforms to workings of
insurance market. Encourages health maintenance organisations.
Trade: Seeks to help create domestic jobs by expanding exports. Has
negotiated Nafta agreement with Canada and Mexico. Seeks similar free trade
agreements in future with other countries in Latin America and eastern
Europe.
Economy
Offers a continuation of Republican Party strategies of past 12 years.
Underlying philosophy is that free markets, low taxes and minimal government
regulation provide best prospect of rapid economic growth and higher living
standards. Thus promises a new round of tax cuts, to be offset by
unspecified cuts in federal spending.
Emphasises the importance of cuts in capital gains taxes as a way of
stimulating private investment and favours short-term incentives to
revitalise the economy, such as tax credits for first-time home buyers and
targeted investment subsidies.
Advocates an amendment ot the Constitution mandating a balanced federal
budget.
Also seeks to strengthen the economy through market-oriented social reforms,
such as the promotion of greater competition to control health care costs
and raise educational standards and the creation of tax-free 'enterprise
zones' to regenerate inner cities. However, the ideas are mostly a late
response to Democratic Party proposals.
BILL CLINTON
Defence: Seeks to maintain strong military, cutting dollars 60bn from Bush's
five-year dollars 1,420bn defence budget. Aims for slightly lower force
levels, mainly by cutting to around 100,000 troops in Europe. Backs
completion of Seawolf and development of Osprey.
Abortion: Supports right to safe, legal abortion, but wants to reduce the
number of abortions. 'Children should not have children.'
Environment: Favours limiting carbon dioxide emissions to 1990 levels by
year 2000 to fight global warming. Supports higher fuel efficiency standards
for cars, more protection for wetlands, old growth forests. Tones down
environmentalist message of his running mate Al Gore.
Healthcare: Plans national health spending caps and universal coverage.
Employers would either provide private insurance or pay into state-run
scheme. Every American guaranteed a basic health benefits package.
Trade: Wants to 'move aggressively to open foreign markets', calling for
stronger 'Super 301' trade bill,  Endorses Nafta, but wants additional job
and environmental protections.
Economy
Advocates a change of economic course involving a greater commitment to
investment in people, a more active role for government and a fairer tax
system.
Supports free enterprise but argues that government can do more to create a
favourable climate for growth. Proposes an additional dollars 200bn of
federal investment in education, training and infrastructure over the next
four years, a more active industrial policy to facilitate the switch from
defence to civilian production, and bold reforms of the health care and
welfare systems.
Advocates modest tax cuts for middle-income families as a way of
compensating for tax cuts that favoured the rich in the 1980s. Would pay for
these reforms by raising taxes on the top 2 per cent of earners, by clamping
down on tax avoidance by foreign companies and by cutting inessential
federal spending. Has pledged to halve budget deficit by 1996.
Critics say the plan lacks fiscal realism and envisages too big a role for
government. Higher taxes on top earners and foreign companies are unlikely
to yield as much revenue as projected, while social reforms - such as
guaranteed health insurance for all - may prove more costly than expected.
ROSS PEROT
Defence: Wants to cut at least dollars 40bn from Bush defence budget over
next five years, eliminating 'relics from the Cold War' like the B2 bomber
and Seawolf. Wants Europe and Asia to pay dollars 100bn more of the cost of
collective security.
Abortion: Supports woman's right to choose. Backs federal funding of
abortions for poor women, but also for education and counselling to reduce
unwanted pregnancies.
Environment: Favours economic incentives rather than regulations to achieve
environmental goals. Wants to end subsidies for inefficient and
environmentally destructive mining and logging activities. Would raise
petrol tax by 10 cents a year for next five years.
Healthcare: Wants short term cost containment and preventitive medicine
programme. Seeks national health board to oversee long-term reform,
including universal coverage.
Trade: Wants to end distinction between the 'high' politics of defence and
diplomacy and the 'low' politics of the economy and jobs. Would put
'experienced, hard-nosed negotiators from outside politics' as trade
negotiators.
Economy
Plan assumes big federal deficits are the root cause of US economic problems
and proposes, unlike other candidates, swingeing cuts in spending and
increases in taxes - enough, he hopes, to eliminate the deficit by 1998.
Theory is that tough action to reduce the deficit would raise the national
savings rate, allow more capital investment and thus boost productivity
growth and living standards.
Asks all sections of society to make sacrifices. The rich would have to pay
higher rates of income tax and face a cap on mortgage interest deductions.
Working families would face sharp increases in petrol and tobacco taxes.
Many elderly people would have to pay more for federal health care and face
higher taxes on pensions. Employer health schemes would be taxed more.
Would increase spending on a few budget items, including research and
development and investment incentives. Overall budget savings estimated at
about dollars 750bn over five years.
Many economists have applauded the tough measures to regain control of the
federal budget, although some fear that deficit reduction at this speed
would risk plunging the economy into a slump.
</TEXT>
