FT  16 OCT 92 / US prices level off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US consumer prices rose a slight 0.2 per cent in September, the government
said yesterday, as a weak economy and wary consumers kept retail inflation
in check, Reuter reports from Washington.
The scant rise brought inflation so far this year to a 2.9 per cent annual
rate. If maintained, that rate would be the lowest since 1986, the
department said.
A 0.7 per cent drop in petrol prices restrained the overall September gain
in the Consumer Price Index, which was down from a 0.3 per cent increase in
August. Excluding volatile food and energy costs, the so-called core rate of
inflation rose 0.2 per cent.
