<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Cabinet insists pit closures plan must go ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH, RALPH ATKINS, DAVID GOODHART and JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CABINET, which had not discussed the drastic programme of pit closures
before it was announced on Tuesday, insisted yesterday the plan had to go
ahead.
It said ministers should make fresh efforts to argue the economic case for
the closures in the face of a rising tide of protest which threatens the
most significant Tory revolt since Mr John Major became prime minister.
Meeting in Sheffield, the National Union of Mineworkers did not call a
strike ballot in the hope of triggering a poll-tax style public revolt on
the issue.
Opposition to the plan is putting at risk the government's majority at
Westminster. The fact it was agreed by a small group of ministers rather
than the full cabinet has increased concern that the full implications were
not addressed.
Senior ministers said the argument for closing 31 of British Coal's 50 pits
with the loss of 30,000 jobs had not been explained sufficiently to get
public support, as the prospect loomed of a significant Tory revolt in next
week's Commons debate on the coal industry.
Downing Street said Mr Major had been 'fully engaged' in the decision, which
had been taken after discussion with the ministers most closely involved.
These included Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary; Mr Tim
Eggar, energy minister; Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment secretary; and Mr
Michael Portillo, Treasury chief secretary.
There was surprise at Westminster, however, that some ministers had been
unaware of the closures before Tuesday's announcement, and that Mr David
Hunt, Welsh secretary, had not been told that Point of Ayr colliery in Wales
would be among the casualties.
The closures appeared to dominate the domestic agenda at yesterday's cabinet
meeting, which lasted two hours instead of the planned 30 minutes.
Adding to the confusion at Westmister, senior Whitehall officials said early
today that the government had brought forward the announcement of the pit
closures in response to a request from British Coal.
The officials said that Mr Major's original intention had been for the
closure programme to be discussed and agreed by the full Cabinet yesterday
and announced in the House of Commons early next week. But the management of
British Coal had asked for authority to make the announcement early this
week following a spate of leaks.
Mr Heseltine is to make a statement on the closures to the Commons when
parliament resumes on Monday, but the critical moment for the government
will come on Wednesday when its 21-strong majority is at risk in the debate
called by Labour.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, has made it clear he is interested in
defeating the closure plans, and is drafting a simple motion intended to
give Tory MPs the least possible excuse for not supporting it. He said it
was 'astonishing and appalling' that the decision had not been taken by
cabinet.
But Mr Tony Newton, the leader of the Commons, defended the handling of the
decision, saying the issues had been 'very thoroughly discussed and fully
assessed by the ministers concerned', who had had the opportunity to talk to
their colleagues.
The need for the government to offer a better explanation for the closures
was underlined by Mr Tom King, a former Tory cabinet minister. He said it
was vital to assure people that 'the implications of this have really been
thought through'. A briefing from Conservative central office has been sent
to every Tory MP, but numerous backbenchers have already made public their
opposition. Protests have come also from Tories outside parliament.
Mr David Nicholson, Tory MP for Taunton, attacked the decision as 'economic
madness'.
The NUM delegate conference in Sheffield decided to try to maximise public
support for a campaign against the closures rather than press for an
immediate strike ballot which many delegates said would be lost.
At the same time the NUM and Nacods, the pit supervisors union, were
applying for an injunction against the closures - the first six of which are
due to take place today - arguing that British Coal failed to consult the
workforce as it is bound to do under the colliery review procedure and both
British and EC employment law.
A High Court judge will today decide whether to grant the injunction, but
most analysts believe there is little chance of the unions succeeding. The
judge said British Coal should take no steps to dismiss miners at the six
pits until he has ruled.
