<HEADLINE>
FT  16 OCT 92 / Major pledges to ratify EC union treaty
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign and Political Staff
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BIRMINGHAM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night offered his European partners an unequivocal
commitment to ratify the Maastricht treaty in spite of the mounting
opposition in his own party.
As the prime minister held a series of bilateral discussions with other
European leaders on the eve of today's Birmingham summit, British officials
voiced confidence that the meeting would end with a clear statement of
intent on the future direction of the Community.
However, they cautioned against expectations of any 'breakthrough' to end
the near-paralysis in the EC caused by the Danish rejection of the treaty.
Mr Major, who will chair the meeting, is looking for a clear pledge on
subsidiarity to help damp opposition in the Tory party ahead of the Commons
debate on Maastricht, paving the way for ratification at the end of the year
or early next year.
Support emerged for Mr Major from both Bonn and Brussels last night. Mr
Jacques Delors, European Commission president, said: 'I recognise that the
political situation in Britain is very difficult. One of the objects of this
(summit) is to help Mr Major and the British government.'
German officials said that Bonn wanted the summit, above all, to be a
success for Mr Major, to strengthen his domestic political position and give
'a signal of confidence' to the rest of the EC.
Britain and Germany appeared to have patched up their quarrel over recent
currency turmoil and German interest rates. After two and a half hours of
talks between Mr Major and Chancellor Helmut Kohl, a UK spokesman said there
was no problem with the German government over sterling's withdrawal from
the European exchange rate mechanism.
'I think the relationship with the German government is very good. The
problems with the Bundesbank are history,' the spokesman said.
During dinner, Mr Kohl reassured Mr Major that there was no question in his
mind of a 'two- or three-speed Europe.' The Community must move ahead as 12,
Mr Kohl said, according to the British spokesman.
A draft declaration presented by the British presidency to other governments
said the 12 should combine reaffirmation of the Maastricht treaty with a
series of pledges to decentralise decision-making, to inject greater
openness into the Community's institutions and to offer reassurance that
European union will not threaten national identities.
However, fundamental disagreements remaining about the precise application
of the principle of decentralisation or 'subsidiarity' mean that the
Birmingham declaration will do little more than commit the leaders to more
detailed decisions at the Edinburgh summit in December.
The Birmingham Summit, Pages 2 and 3
Three personal views, Page 21
High stakes, low hopes, Page 22
Editorial Comment, Page 22
