<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / UK shoots itself in the foot over wild birds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK's latest row with the European Commission over the shooting of wild
birds has turned out to be not only a storm in a teacup - but one of
Britain's own making.
Senior Commission officials yesterday confirmed that the prohibition against
farmers and sportsmen shooting birds such as crows and woodpigeons was
inserted in the relevant 1979 directive at the insistence of member states,
chief among them the UK. The Commission's original proposal 'specifically
said pest birds could be shot', said Mr Karel Van Miert, the EC environment
commissioner.
'It's unfair to accuse the Commission on something we didn't originally
want,' he added.
The dispute was seized on, particularly in the British media, as an example
of the sort of meddling by Brussels which the member states will discuss how
to stop at tomorrow's Birmingham summit of EC heads of government.
On Monday, after prominent reports that the Commission was prosecuting the
UK over the issue, Mr Douglas Hurd told the House of Commons foreign affairs
select committee that such isues were 'a matter for national governments
acting in line with national traditions, national feelings'.
The prosecution, launched after complaints from British wildlife
organisations that the government was not enforcing the law, had in any case
been dropped in June.
Brussels shelved the case, Mr Van Miert said, because the Commission is
preparing an amendment to the wild birds directive.
This amendment would turn the directive back towards the original Brussels
proposal allowing the shooting of pest species.
'The original reasoning is still valid,' he said, but the prosecutions went
ahead 'because that is what the law said.' Mr Van Miert also revealed that
the Commission is working up proposals for the decentralised implementation
and monitoring of EC environment legislation.
This would be a pragmatic response to the UK's proposal for an EC
inspectorate to make sure all member states comply with EC law.
This is a plan several member states regard as the sort of intrusion into
national affairs Britain says it is trying to halt.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
