FT  15 OCT 92 / Key senator demands prosecutor on BNL
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE was building in Congress last night for the US administration to
reconsider its refusal to appoint a special prosecutor to investigate the
government's handling of the scandal over Dollars 5bn of illegal loans to
Iraq, made by the Atlanta branch of Italy's Banca Nazionale del Lavoro
(BNL).
The increased pressure came as Senator David Boren, the conservative
Democratic chairman of the Senate intelligence committee, demanded that a
special prosecutor be named to investigate the BNL-Iraq affair.
He has been holding closed Senate hearings to determine why the CIA and
Justice Department concealed information on the BNL affair from a US federal
court.
Mr Boren said last night that new information had come to light in the past
two weeks that should compel Mr William Barr, US Attorney-General, to
appoint a special prosecutor.
In a letter to Mr Barr yesterday, Mr Boren said the CIA had admitted that,
with the 'strong advice' of the Justice Department, it had written a
misleading letter about BNL to US prosecutors in Atlanta.
Mr Boren cited what he called 'an unprecedented statement' from Judge Marvin
Shoob of the BNL case in Atlanta, which stated that 'decisions were made at
the top levels of the US government and within the intelligence community to
shape this case.'
Mr Boren said 'a truly independent investigation is required to determine
whether federal crimes were committed' in the government's handling of the
BNL affair.
</TEXT>
