<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DIGITAL Equipment, the struggling US computer manufacturer, reported
heavier-than-expected losses for its first fiscal quarter, citing weakness
in leading economies.
The loss for the quarter was Dollars 260.5m, or Dollars 2.04 per share,
compared with a net loss, after charges, of Dollars 474m, or Dollars 3.80,
in the first quarter last year. Revenues were Dollars 3.31bn, up 1 per cent
on last year.
'Weakness in the world's major economies continues to present difficult
challenges for our business and the information technology industry in
general,' said Mr John Smith, senior vice-president of operations. 'We
continue to eliminate costs in accordance with our recovery plan,' said Mr
William M. Steul, vice-president, finance.
Research and development spending declined by about 1.6 per cent on a
year-to-year basis, and the workforce was cut by 5,300 in the first quarter,
he added. 'We will continue our aggressive restructuring and cost reduction
efforts.'
Mr Robert Palmer, who succeeded Digital's founder, Mr Kenneth Olsen, as
president and chief executive last month, vowed to improve Digital's
financial performance.
'Digital will change,' he said. 'We are intent on ensuring that the customer
is the focus of everything that we do. Moreover, our shareholders and
customers want and expect us to be financially strong. Every activity that
we undertake is guided by the goals of customer focus and a return to
profitable growth.
Digital said revenues from its systems integration services, workstations,
personal computers, integration software and network applications support
products grew during the quarter.
