<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / International Company News: Bear Stearns follows industry
trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BEAR Stearns, the Wall Street broking house, yesterday unveiled fiscal
first-quarter earnings of Dollars 63m, substantially higher than a year ago
but well below the extremely strong profits of the previous two quarters. At
the same stage last year, the firm earned Dollars 47.1m.
Bear Stearns' earnings repeated a pattern seen at most big Wall Street firms
in the current reporting season, with strong trading and investment banking
earnings offsetting weak brokerage business.
Revenues from own-account trading jumped sharply, rising 41 per cent to
Dollars 250.7m, due to favourable conditions in international financial
markets. Investment banking revenues rose 15.3 per cent to Dollars 62.4m in
the wake of a busy corporate securities underwriting calendar.
Interest income, however, was sharply lower at Dollars 204.5m in the wake of
further declines in domestic interest rates, and broking commissions were
virtually flat at Dollars 84.9m following reduced investor activity in the
stock markets over the summer.
Total corporate expenses rose 20 per cent between July and September to
Dollars 330.5m, primarily due to a big increase in employee pay and benefits
linked to market performance and profitability.
During the quarter the company bought 1.6m shares of its common stock, worth
about Dollars 25m, for a deferred compensation plan for senior managing
directors.
</TEXT>
