FT  15 OCT 92 / Watchdog to probe sale of PSA unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Audit Office, the government's spending watchdog, is to
investigate the sale of the Property Services Agency's projects division to
Tarmac, Britain's largest construction and building materials company.
The investigation is to start within weeks of the completion of the deal at
the end of November.
The government agreed this month to pay Tarmac almost Pounds 50m to take
over responsibility for the division, one of the country's biggest
construction organisations, employing 1,800 people. About half those jobs
are now at risk.
The NAO investigation will be followed by an inquiry by the all-party
Commons public accounts committee.
The terms of the sale were challenged yesterday by Mr Jack Straw, shadow
environment secretary, who urged the European Commission to investigate it.
'This is one of the most bizarre privatisations ever. It represents a
triumph of arid dogma over the public interest and over the probity of
public finance,' he said.
Mr John Redwood, the local government minister, vigorously denied that there
was any impropriety in the deal.
