<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Doubt over rail freight sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, LISA WOOD and IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MILLIONS OF tonnes of coal traffic will be lost as a result of the pit
closure programme, worsening the outlook for the planned sale of BR's
freight businesses as part of the privatisation process next year. Several
thousand jobs in British Rail's coal train business are also likely to go.
The closures are a particularly severe blow for BR because Trainload Coal,
its coal-carrying business, is virtually the only profitable part of the
railway.
Trainload Coal's business consists almost entirely of carrying coal from
pits to power stations. Last year it carried 75m tonnes, but British Coal
says power stations are expected to take only 40m tonnes next year.
BR will not say how many are employed by Trainload Coal, but the figure is
believed to be 7,000. Up to half seem likely to lose their jobs.
The downturn in business will jeopardise other parts of the railway because
operations that share tracks, engine sheds or other facilities with
Trainload Coal may not be viable if required to support the full costs of
those assets alone.
Operations likely to be affected include other parts of the Trainload
Freight business - Trainload Construction, Trainload Petroleum and Trainload
Metals. Trainload Freight reported turnover of Pounds 505.3m last year, of
which Trainload Coal is believed to have contributed Pounds 300m.
Mr Derrick Fullick, general secretary of the train drivers' union Aslef,
said he feared that 11 engine sheds would be affected and that eight of them
would have to close. Those most likely to be affected are the Stoke and
Sunderland depots.
Mr Frank Dobson, shadow employment secretary, claimed yesterday that up to
50,000 jobs in areas related to mining would be lost.
Mr Andrew Glyn, an economist at Corpus Christi College, Oxford, estimated
that a total of 78,600 jobs would disappear.
Mr Dobson named 65 engineering and component supplier companies that might
be affected. He said jobs in companies supplying the mining industry in
towns as far away as Bracknell and Basingstoke were threatened.
Labour said jobs were at stake among private contractors working in
maintenance. Nacods, the supervisors union, says 15,000 contractors are
employed by British Coal. BC said it could not confirm that because it
employed companies, not individuals.
</TEXT>
