<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Call for reform of intangibles reporting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES should include both purchased and internally created intangible
assets on their balance sheets, according to a study sponsored by the
Accounting Standards Board and the research board of the Institute of
Chartered Accountants in England and Wales.
Intangible assets are non-physical assets such as brand names which a
growing number of companies are showing in their accounts with little
guidance on their treatment.
The Manchester University study will intensify the debate over whether
intangibles should be recognised. It says intangibles should be included
provided the existence and amount can be justified. It also wants greater
disclosure of the nature of valuations.
Goodwill and other intangibles. Research Board, ICAEW, PO Box 433, Moorgate
Place, London EC2P 2BJ. Pounds 10.
Accountancy Column, Page 12
