<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow sees modest fall after
erratic trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US STOCK markets ended a see-saw day with modest losses yesterday as
investors continued to digest the latest round of third quarter corporate
results, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 5.94 at 3,195.48.
After opening lower, the index recovered to post a 15-point gain by early
afternoon, before selling in the futures market sent it to a 20-point
decline at 3.30pm, a decline that was only partially reversed in the last
few minutes of trading.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 ended 0.02 firmer at 409.32,
while the Amex composite eased 0.66 to 366.17 and the Nasdaq composite fell
0.21 to 576.23. Turnover on the NYSE was 174m shares.
Losses in Tokyo, London and other European markets set the tone for a
downbeat opening in New York, and after two days of substantial gains, there
was no real resistance to early selling, mainly by European investors. The
release of the latest economic news - a 0.3 per cent rise in both retail
sales and producer prices during September - had little impact on sentiment.
As some more good third quarter corporate earnings figures came in, shares
soon regained the ground lost in the first half-hour, but amid continued
uncertainty about the economic, political and earnings outlook prices
fluctuated wildly for the remainder of the session.
One of the best corporate stories of the day was Coca-Cola, which climbed
Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 38 1/2 in turnover of 1.7m shares after the soft
drinks giant announced third quarter profits of 41 cents a share, up from 34
cents a share a year ago. The company also said it was 'on track' for 'very
strong' earnings for the full year.
Pepsico, which also reported strong quarterly profits on Tuesday, was
firmer, up Dollars  3/8 at Dollars 39. Bank of New York rose Dollars 1/2 to
Dollars 44 5/8 in busy trading after the bank reported a 66 per cent rise in
earnings to Dollars 1.07 a share. Another regional banking group, Republic
New York, was unchanged at Dollars 43 after news that it had won approval
from the Federal Reserve to conduct full-service securities brokerage
business through a subsidiary.
International Paper fell Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 61 1/8 after the broking
house, Dean Witter Reynolds, lowered its rating on the stock from a 'hold'
to a 'swap' to reflect the postponement of price increases for linerboard
and uncoated free sheet paper.
On the Nasdaq market, selected leading technology issues were higher, with
Apple up Dollars  5/8 at Dollars 46 and Borland International up Dollars 1
5/8 at 29 5/8 .
Canada
TORONTO share prices closed lower in moderate trading, following the trend
set in major world markets. According to preliminary data, the 300 composite
index lost 19.46 points, or 0.61 per cent, to close at 3,195.39. Declines
led advances by 304 to 201, volume of 23.6m shares was below the previous
24.5m, and trading value was CDollars 215.6m against CDollars 183.6m.
</TEXT>
