<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / World Stock Markets (Europe): Bourses mixed before
Bundesbank meeting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The continent put in a mixed performance yesterday, and trading remained
thin ahead of today's Bundesbank meeting, writes Our Markets Staff.
FRANKFURT fell as the government was told to raise income tax allowances,
the market taking the view that the lost revenue would have to be made up
elsewhere. Among individual stocks, Veba came under pressure as the Dax
index ended 6.97 lower at 1,458.53.
Veba fell DM10.90 to DM341.10, hit by two rumours: that the company faced
large costs for environmental cleaning at a Berlin site, though this was
denied by the company; and that Dresdner Bank had downgraded its earnings
forecasts for the utility group, but this was also denied by the bank.
Leading chemicals were also the subject of profit revisions from two
research houses, DB Research and CSFB, which cut back their profit forecasts
and predicted 1992 dividend cuts from Hoechst and BASF. But dealers said the
news had no impact on the sector which moved in line with the market.
Pharmaceutical shares, led by Degussa and Schering, posted the day's
strongest gains. Degussa closed at DM287, up DM8.50 Schering DM13 higher at
DM663.
MILAN jumped 2.7 per cent on the final day of the October trading account on
a combination of professional short-covering and buying by domestic funds
and brokers in anticipation of a firm start to the new account. But foreign
investors were largely absent, taking the view that the recent rally was
mainly technical. The Comit index rose 10.48 to 404.76 in turnover estimated
at a high L250bn after Tuesday's L164bn.
Fiat and Generali continued to fuel the market's rise. Fiat rose L291 or 7.1
per cent to to L4,391 on continued rumours, denied by the company, that the
car group was close to some kind of agreement with Toyota of Japan. Fiat was
also lifted by the short covering of a reported 12m shares. Generali rose
L1,150 or 4.2 per cent to L28,760.
PARIS remained short on ideas, which was reflected in the paltry turnover of
FFr1.28bn. The CAC-40 index ended 17.16 down at 1,667.93.
Euro Disney continued to rise, adding FFr1.80 to FFr76.50, but off the day's
high of FFr77.80, on a report that its US parent planned to reduce the
financial pressure on its subsidiary.
The fall in the dollar contributed to the decline in building material
stocks, with Lafarge losing FFr8.50 to FFr271 and Saint-Gobain dropping
FFr14 to FFr482.
AMSTERDAM finished on a weaker note, following a softer dollar and declines
on most European bourses. The CBS Tendency Index fell 0.4 to 106.7.
Chemicals shares sustained the heaviest losses as several analysts
downgraded their profit forecasts. DSM fell Fl 1.50 to Fl 87.80 and Akzo
lost Fl 1.40 to Fl 133.40.
MADRID followed the downtrend established elsewhere, the general index
closing 1.03 lower at 191.65. The talking point of the day was the fall of
Pta45 to Pta925 in Telefonica, apparently due to selling by one domestic
broker. The company held a presentation for analysts in Madrid yesterday,
but this was expected to be neutral in its effect.
OSLO closed mixed with the airline, DNL, up and rig stocks down. As the
all-share index fell 1.05 to 335.91, DNL rose NKr2 to NKr58 on news that a
small competitor named Norway Airlines faced bankruptcy. Most rig shares
fell after rising by some 30 per cent in a week, Wilrig losing NKr5 to NKr20
and Ross Offshore NKr3 to NKr24.
STOCKHOLM was little changed as the Affarsvarlden General index eased 0.9 to
674.9 in turnover of SKr354m after SKr264m.
Astra remained firm, with its A shares adding SKr7 to SKr517, while
profit-taking took Procordia B shares down from SKr74 to closed unchanged at
SKr69.
S-E Banken C shares fell SKr0.50 to SKr12.50 ahead of its eight-month
earnings report today.
VIENNA's 18-share ATX index rose just 0.06 to 778.73 in quiet trading ahead
of the Bundesbank meeting today.
ZURICH's SMI index fell 4.2 to 1,889.3. Chemicals saw some profit-taking,
with Ciba bearers SFr9 easier at SFr621.
HELSINKI was slightly higher ahead of interim results from five Finnish
banks today. The HEX index rose 0.35 to 606.78.
