<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / UK Company News: N Brown beats Pounds 7m aided by core
growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
N BROWN, the mail order company which specialises in clothing for older
women, yesterday announced a 23 per cent profits rise due to growth in both
core and new business.
Pre-tax profits increased from Pounds 6.03m to Pounds 7.44m in the six
months to August 29. Turnover was 14 per cent up at Pounds 79.6m (Pounds
69.5m), helped by Pounds 3.79m of sales from Odhams, the video and compact
disc order company acquired from the receiver last November.
Operating profits increased only 2.4 per cent to Pounds 9.4m. They were held
back by spending to improve customer service and low operating margins at
Odhams of 3 per cent, against 13.1 per cent for Brown's established
business.
Mr Jim Martin, chief executive, said Brown's emphasis on selling to older
women offered protection from the recession. Orders had increased strongly
since August, although the situation had worsened following sterling's
withdrawal from the ERM.
Interest costs declined to Pounds 1.81m (Pounds 2.28m) helped by the
proceeds of last year's Pounds 16.4m placing and open offer. Income from
listed investments, mainly referring to a stake in Coats Viyella, increased
to Pounds 107,000 (Pounds 93,000). Brown's small financial and property arm
incurred an operating loss of Pounds 33,000.
As part of the focus on customer service, products are being brought into
Brown's warehouse earlier, reducing delays between orders and delivery.
However, this lead to a 14 per cent increase in stocks on a like-for-like
basis to Pounds 27.3m.
Net borrowings in the period increased to Pounds 32.8m (Pounds 31.7m). But
gearing fell from 56 per cent to 49 per cent due to a 12 per cent increase
in shareholders' funds to Pounds 67.1m.
Earnings rose 14 per cent to 6.84p (5.99p). The interim dividend is lifted
to 1.95p (1.75p).
COMMENT
Brown and its products may be short on glamour, but the company has solid
support in the stock market, which respects its defensive nature and ability
to grow profits from a niche market. Its emphasis on improving customer
service may constrain growth this year but should begin to pay dividends
next year. Customer queries, which have fallen 18 per cent in a year due to
an improved billing system, should continue to drop along with the
proportion of goods returned. Meanwhile, Odhams' full-year contribution
should top Pounds 400,000 and provide a useful side line. Despite
yesterday's 7p rise in the shares to 288p, Brown's price has been fairly
flat following a 41 per cent increase last year. Full-year forecasts of
Pounds 18m put the shares on 17 times earnings, which is below the sector
average, suggesting that they can go a little higher yet.
</TEXT>
