FT  15 OCT 92 / Observer: Some contest
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, has thrown down the
gauntlet on subsidiarity.
Vexed by MEPs' calls for an off-the-cuff explanation of Brussels' position
on the ill-defined principle that EC decisions should be taken at the lowest
appropriate level, Delors told yesterday's special session of the European
Parliament that a concise summary was impossible.
What was more, he said, the Commission would be happy to offer employment
and a Ecu 200,000 salary to anyone who could produce a one-page explanation
of how subsidiarity might work. The 'secret' subsidiarity paper produced by
Delors' own aides runs to 23 pages.
One MEP who has already risen to Delors' tongue-in-cheek challenge is
British Conservative Edward McMillan-Scott. He has already produced a
summary of the Maastricht treaty changes on two sides of a postcard - with
room to spare for his photograph - and was last night trying to reduce it to
competition size.
Delors has not suggested who might be the judge of such a contest; if he
were inundated with entries, perhaps the concept of subsidiarity might be
brought into play.
</TEXT>
