<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Television cookery programmes have improved out of all recognition. True,
you do still come across the occasional man with a camp hairdo and a silly
accent standing behind a studio gas stove telling you that this is one he
made earlier, but increasingly rarely.
Setting the standard today are series such as Keith Floyd's on Spain where
the sharing of recipes is just one among a number of ambitions. A Cook's
Tour Of France with its location camerawork and interest in local traditions
and personalities has much more in common with Floyd than with the old
studio gas stove routine.
Here the hostess is Mireille Johnston who today visits Brittany (8.00 BBC2).
Given the current scarcity of good British comedies it seems odd of BBC1 to
screen Waiting For God and the repeats of One Foot In The Grave on the same
night (8.30 &amp; 10.20), especially since both are concerned with the modern
tribulations of old age.
BBC2's series about life in Britain today, Present Imperfect (9.30) looks
tonight at Steve and Dennis, travelling evangelists who use video and pop
music to appeal to their target audience: children.
</TEXT>
