<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Whalen calls for cut in interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Geoffrey Whalen, chief executive of Peugeot-Talbot, the UK subsidiary of
the French carmaker, last night called for a cut of 1 percentage point in
interest rates 'as soon as possible', Kevin Done writes.
He said that the government should not embark on a 'mad dash for growth' and
added that any reduction should 'not be of such a size as to threaten the
control of inflation'.
He said that an early return to the European exchange rate mechanism should
be ruled out, as that would prevent the cut in interest rates that the
economy desperately needed.
He said that industry needed 'to be persuaded that when the government says
that it cares about the survival and future well-being of British
manufacturing industry, it really means it.
'As a first and basic step, all cabinet ministers should be told that in all
that they and their departments do, manufacturing industry's needs ought to
be considered with the greatest care.'
