<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Uphill struggle for the labour market: Jobless totals may
not peak until 1995
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE recent surge in announcements of job losses from some of Britain's
best-known companies has renewed speculation about when, and at what level,
unemployment will reach its peak.
As recently as two months ago, government economists were confident that
unemployment would not touch 3m. That now seems highly optimistic.
Many independent economists now say unemployment will peak at just over 3m -
a little under 11 per cent of the workforce - at the end of next year or
early in 1994. Some are more pessimistic, suggesting that the growth in
unemployment will not cease until 1995.
Confusion over the government's economic policy, in particular over
movements in interest rates, makes it difficult for economists to forecast
when unemployment will start to fall. The worst-case scenario of Ernst &amp;
Young's Item Club - a forecasting body that uses the Treasury's economic
model - sees an early return to the European exchange rate mechanism and
tighter monetary policy. That might delay the recovery, in which case
unemployment is projected to peak at about 3.6m in 1995.
Even in that scenario, the lag between a resumption of growth and and a
turnround in unemployment is expected to be shorter than it was in the early
1980s. When the economy started to emerge from recession in early 1981, the
jobless level continued to rise until 1986, when it peaked at a rate of 11
per cent.
This time, economists expect the lag to be much shorter. They argue that
reforms affecting the labour market have created a much swifter link between
a fall in output and a rise in unemployment, and conversely between an
increase in output and a fall in unemployment.
Another influence that should help to shorten the unemployment lag is
demographic. Between 1981 and 1985, the working population was growing at an
average of 200,000 a year as a result of the 1960s baby boom. Between 1991
and 1995 the working population will grow at only 20,000 a year.
Recent announcements of further big job losses in the manufacturing sector
have led to fears that there has been an acceleration in the trend growth
rate of the jobless total from 30,000 a month.
Mr John Philpott, director of the Employment Policy Institute, the
independent think tank, says: 'It seems that a lot of employers were holding
back over the summer, waiting to see what would happen to the economy. As
the recovery still appears to be a long way off, employers have embarked on
another round of big redundancies.'
Apart from the most recent British Coal announcement this week, many of the
recent cuts have hit the south-east disproportionately hard. The defence and
electronics industries - such as those at British Aerospace - appear to have
taken the brunt of recent cuts and both have a strong presence in the
south-east.
According to the latest survey by Hay Management Consultants on the
distribution of job losses across the UK as a whole, the manufacturing,
engineering and service sectors have suffered worst.
But Mr David Fell, economist at Business Strategies, the economics
consultancy, says that although unemployment is rising fastest in the
south-east and the south-west, the level was lower in those regions at the
start of the recession.
Nevertheless he believes that regional differences in unemployment rates
will be smaller in the future. However, the overall rates being predicted by
Business Strategies for the mid 1990s look frighteningly high. It sees rates
of above 10 per cent for every region apart from Wales and East Anglia, with
the south-west at 15.3 per cent, the west Midlands at 14.4 per cent, and the
north-west at 14 per cent.
The recent devaluation of sterling might help those companies producing for
export or in competition with imports, but it may take some time to show.
Government economists point to the fact that even before the pound came out
of the ERM on September 16, unit labour costs were growing at about the same
rate as those of the UK's main competitors.
So, in spite of the recent acceleration in unemployment, there is one ray of
hope. The devaluation of sterling will give exporters a costs benefit,
enabling them to expand market share, which should eventually boost
employment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
