<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Maternity seen as handicap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY WOMEN with prof-essional or managerial jobs feel their career prospects
are damaged after taking a break to have a baby.
The finding comes in a survey covering nearly 800 women, published today by
Sussex University and carried out on behalf of leading employers including
Marks and Spencer, Barclays Bank, the Treasury, Shell (UK) and the Wellcome
Foundation.
Before taking a career break, 84 per cent of women were very satisfied or
satisfied with the way they were promoted at work. After returning to work,
that dropped to 64 per cent.
Ms Wendy Hirsh, co-author of the report, said women felt employers were
taking an increasingly positive attitude to providing career breaks.
'However, they are much less sure about their future career opportunities.
Many feel their careers have to take a back seat, at least for a while, and
that their line managers see them as less promotable once they have become
mothers.'
Evidence of discrimination in promotion was not established by the survey.
Only 9 per cent of the sample returned to a job at a lower level than before
the career break; a third had been promoted within a short time of returning
to work and substantial numbers had made sideways moves. The researchers had
no comparable figures for men.
Beyond the Career Break. IMS report no 223 by Wendy Hirsh, Sue Hayday, Jill
Yeates and Claire Callender. Institute of Manpower Studies, University of
Sussex, Falmer, Brigh-ton, Sussex BN1 9RF. Pounds 30 (IMS subscribers Pounds
24) plus Pounds 1.75 p&amp;p.
</TEXT>
