<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / CBI plea to PM on Europe: Employers urge caution over
re-entry to exchange rate mechanism
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Confederation of British Industry called on Mr John Major, the prime
minister, yesterday to ensure that Britain did not risk its economic future
by becoming a 'semi-detached' member of the European community.
The plea, which was issued as the prime minister prepares for tomorrow's EC
summit in Birmingham, was accompanied by a warning that Britain should not
re-enter the European exchange rate mechanism until tensions have eased
between German and British monetary policy.
The CBI also emphasised that the government should do nothing to close off
the option of re-entry.
In a letter to Mr Major, the CBI criticised aspects of the community's
development and the performance of the EC Commission, but it quoted the
prime minister in contending that Britain had to remain at the heart of
Europe.
Sir Michael Angus, CBI president, voiced concern that any failure by Britain
to ratify the Maastricht treaty would transmit the wrong signals about the
country's future position in the community and damage its ability to attract
critical inward investment.
Sir Michael said that the Birmingham summit had to make progress on the
issue of subsidiarity, which needed to be emphasised and expanded in a clear
summit declaration.
The powers of the Commission, he added, had to be more tightly constrained,
although it also needed to ensure that member states were not able to
provide financial assistance to industry through 'the back door of
subsidiarity'.
Sir Michael called on Mr Major to press for improvements in the way the
Commission conducts its business, suggesting the wider use of green papers
to ensure that the implications of proposed directives are fully understood
by the business community.
Sir Michael criticised the Commission for failing to enforce single market
directives evenly across the community. He said CBI members resented the
Commission's 'intrusive and sometimes erratic' approach to regulation and
legislation, and called on Mr Major to press home measures to complete the
single market, an objective that was being overlooked in the broader debate
over the community's future.
</TEXT>
