</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS leaders in the west Midlands anxious for more inward investment to
stimulate the regional economy, are demanding closer co-ordination by the
many organisations responsible for attracting companies to the region.
A survey by Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountancy firm, in Birmingham, found
that about three quarters of 300 private and public-sector executives
perceived conflicts of interests between the organisations involved.
More than half the private-sector executives and nearly three quarters of
the public-sector executives were dissatisfied with regional promotion.
The disquiet reflects the downturn of inward investment in the region over
the past two years. During the 1980s, the west Midlands successful in
attracting overseas companies. In 1986-90, 21 per cent of British inward
investment projects went to the west Midlands, a figure that dropped to 14
per cent last year.
