<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Ministers weigh future of London's hospitals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS will today begin considering a report which is likely to lead to
the biggest ever shake-up in London's hospital services.
The final version of the report by Sir Bernard Tomlinson, former chairman of
the Northern Regional Health Authority, is in the hands of Mrs Virginia
Bottomley, health secretary. Mrs Bottomley - who has received regular
progress reports from Sir Bernard during his year-long investigation of
health provision in London - will publish the report around the end of this
month.
There will then be a period of consultation - and furious campaigning by
hospitals identified for closure - before ministers make final decisions in
the new year.
Some of the capital's most famous teaching hospitals - including St
Bartholomew's, St Thomas', University College, the Middlesex and Charing
Cross - have been considered for closure or change of use during Sir
Bernard's inquiry.
In a last-minute submission to Sir Bernard last week, the St Thomas'
management said the capital costs associated with closing either St Thomas'
or the neighbouring Guy's teaching hospital would be so great as to 'negate
for at least the first 10 years' any revenue savings.'
St Thomas' management argued that both hospitals should survive, with St
Thomas' concentrating on emergency and local work and Guy's developing
specialist services.
Under that plan, three local hospitals in south London - Hither Green in
Lewisham, Dulwich in Southwark and Brook in Greenwich - would close instead
of either of the teaching hospitals.
Guy's accident and emergency department would close under the plan, which
argues that a combination of St Thomas' and University College hospitals
would provide the most effective emergency cover for central London.
No solution excluding St Thomas', the submission says, would provide cover
within 10 minutes for Whitehall and state occasions in Westminster.
The St Thomas' research draws on work commissioned from Ernst and Young,
management consultants, transport specialists at Imperial College, London,
and other sources.
In its submission, the St Thomas' management challenges the view of South
East Thames Regional Health Authority that either St Thomas' or Guy's could
close - eliminating 800 beds in addition to other rationalisation plans in
south London.
There is, the submission says, no evidence that local health services in
south London would be in place to support reduced demand on hospital beds.
</TEXT>
