<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Democrats seek to dispel potent magic: What Bill Clinton
would like America to think about James Baker
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INSIDE the Beltway and around the world, James Addison Baker 3rd is a name
mentioned with serious reverence. Beyond Washington's ring road and inside
the nation's boundaries, the perception is less sharp.
But it is this second market that he is now seeking to reclaim, not for the
first time, for George Bush. Not only is he again running the president's
struggling re-election campaign, he has now been requested to shape economic
policy and create a new economic team for a second term, if there is one.
In either fear or recognition, perhaps both, of his reputation, Bill
Clinton's campaign banged out an indictment of Mr Baker within hours of Mr
Bush's mentioning his new role in the first televised debate on Sunday. It
includes subjects rarely mentioned in the polite Washington society that the
current White House chief of staff holds in thrall.
For example, that, as President Reagan's first chief of staff, he was 'the
political mastermind behind efforts to cut taxes for the wealthy and
services for everybody else'; that, as treasury secretary in the second
Reagan term, he 'presided over the most disastrous finance debacle in recent
history - the Dollars 500bn savings and loan scandal'; that, as Bush's
secretary of state, he played 'a central role' in 'the secret policy of aid
to Saddam Hussein'.
It got more personal: that Mr Baker was a notorious frequent user of
military jets while on personal business; that the Baker plan for third
world debt was also designed to protect his own private holdings in a big US
bank; that he is partner in an oil barge business which successfully lobbied
to prevent the enactment of expensive environmental rules.
Mr Baker has not stooped to respond, except for one little incident. Flying
commercially from St Louis, he resisted the invitation from the cabin crew
to move up to first class.
No contemporary public figure, certainly none who has never won an election
and only run once - for Texas attorney-general in 1978 - has commanded such
mystique. To his admirers, who are many, he is the consummate deal-maker
able to work effectively in Washington and from Brussels to Beijing.
To his detractors, who are growing in number, he has the extraordinary
facility to do bad as well as good, but never, never to get the blame for
anything that goes wrong.
Mr Baker, a Houston patrician polished by an Ivy League university,
Princeton, is said to dislike politics. He has admitted he found his 1978
race personally 'distasteful'.
His relationship with Mr Bush goes back 30 years and must be complex. He may
be smarter than his president, and is reported to have no compunction about
ordering him around in private, but is dependent on his patronage. Each, it
seems, serves the other's needs.
In his farewell speech in August to the state department, where he was not
universally admired, he said that he was only leaving - 'one of the most
difficult decisions of my life' - because he believed in the necessity of
global US leadership. He then recited a long list of accomplishments.
By this logic, Mr Baker is only doing what he is now in order to go back to
what he was doing as soon as possible. A short intermission in control of
domestic policy, if the electorate grants that, seems the limit of his
desire.
A reluctance ever to create public hostages to fortune has always been his
trademark, as much in negotiations in the Middle East as in his various
political roles. It explains why some people even speculate that he could be
useful to a President Clinton on some specially-defined mission, if not
immediately, then after the passage of a decent interval. This week's
Democratic indictment of him makes this now a little fanciful.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 5
