<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Anxiety over weak sales rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WEAK retail sales statistics and climbing producer prices yesterday did
nothing to dispel anxiety about the US economy.
The Commerce Department said retail sales rose by 0.3 per cent in September
to Dollars 161.1bn. But much of the increase came from sales of building
materials and home furnishings. Economists suggested this was temporary
because of rebuilding after Hurricane Andrew had hit southern Florida.
The producer price index, meanwhile, rose in September by 0.3 per cent from
the previous month, the Labour Department announced, to show year-on-year
wholesale price inflation of 1.6 per cent.
Energy prices rose by 0.8 per cent during September, after small declines in
July and August. Consumer food prices continued to rise, though at a slower
pace than in August.
Consumer goods, without the volatile food and energy components, rose by 0.2
per cent, helped by dearer tobacco.
Prices of intermediate supplies and components rose by 0.2 per cent in
September, to show slower year-on-year inflation of 0.9 per cent.
</TEXT>
