<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Airbus chief wants a Nasa for Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOULOUSE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE HEAD of Airbus Industrie yesterday called for a European equivalent of
the US National Aeronautical and Space Administration (Nasa) to be set up in
order to fund research and development in European commercial aerospace
programmes.
Mr Jean Pierson, the consortium's managing director, said it was crucial for
governments to give greater backing to commercial aircraft programmes at a
time when the US, through Nasa, was increasing support for its aircraft
industry.
Such action had become all the more important with the sharp decline in the
defence business which had traditionally supported research and development
funding in commercial projects.
Mr Pierson suggested that some of the Dollars 800m in launch aid which
Airbus was due to repay this year should go to research and technology
development for future commercial aircraft. 'The Airbus partners (France,
Germany, Britain and Spain) must now invest in the longer-term future,' he
said. 'If you want to survive, you must look ahead and invest.'
Mr Pierson made his proposal as the European consortium rolled out its
latest airliner, the twin-engine, wide-bodied A330. Company officials said
the consortium's operations now directly employed about 60,000 people in
Europe. In the UK alone, 300 companies were working on Airbus business.
Airbus has become increasingly concerned by disagreements among its partners
on significant aerospace projects, especially the European fighter aircraft
(EFA), and new regional aircraft programmes.
They warned that the dispute between Britain and Germany over the future of
the EFA could have serious repercussions on European aerospace collaboration
on the civil side.
Mr Pierson said: 'We must be very careful to remain united in our goal to
build up a successful commercial European aircraft industry if we don't want
to lose out to our American competitors in 10 years' time.'
Airbus this week announced a further scaling down in its aircraft production
rate over the next three years in response to the slump in civil aviation.
It has also delayed the launch of the A319, a shortened version of its A320
twin-engine, 150-seater.
The consortium is expected to show another operating profit this year after
reporting a surplus of about Dollars 250m (Pounds 145.3m) last year. Mr
Pierson said the European partners could not 'just sleep' because of the
commercial success of the consortium which had gained a 26 per cent share of
the world commercial airliner market in the past 20 years.
</TEXT>
