<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / UN prepares for transfer of Serb aircraft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS and LAURA SILBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA, BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PREPARATIONS were under way yesterday for the rapid transfer of all
Bosnian-Serb combat aircraft to United Nations-monitored airfields in the
rump Yugoslavia, after Mr Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian-Serb leader, agreed
to the measure in Geneva on Tuesday night.
A senior representative of the UN protection force (Unprofor) in the former
Yugoslavia is due in Banja Luka, military headquarters of the Bosnian Serbs,
later this week to arrange the transfer, which has also been agreed by Mr
Milan Panic, the Yugoslav prime minister. The UN representative will be
accompanied by a Yugoslav air force officer.
Mr Karadzic made the offer after being warned by Lord Owen, the EC mediator
on ex-Yugoslavia, that the UN Security Council would move swiftly to enforce
its ban on military flights over Bosnia imposed October 9.
According to intelligence reports available to the UN, Bosnian-Serb aircraft
bombed the Moslem-held city of Gradacac on October 10, flying more than 20
sorties, but have since been grounded. Bosnian-Serb leaders have denied the
Gradacac bombing raids.
Under the terms of the new accord, all military fixed-wing and helicopter
aircraft intended for use in combat and stationed on Bosnian territory will
be transferred to airfields in Serbia and Montenegro, where they will be
monitored by Unprofor observers. UN officials said yesterday they hoped the
aircraft would be moved within the next few days.
Banja Luka is the main airbase for Bosnian-Serb forces, but neither the UN
nor the Bosnian Serbs have revealed the number of aircraft stationed there
or elsewhere in Bosnia-Hercegovina.
UN officials acknowledge that the deal will be a crucial test of whether Mr
Karadzic has, as he claims, full control over Bosnian-Serb commanders in the
field. A spokesman for Lord Owen said yesterday that Mr Karadzic's offer had
been taken up on the understanding that he was 'fully capable to deliver'.
However, the Bosnian-Serb air force commander said on Tuesday night that he
had not been consulted on the proposal to hand over the aircraft.
Lord Owen and Mr Cyrus Vance, the UN mediator, hope Bosnian-Serb compliance
with the UN 'no-fly zone' will help pave the way for broader agreement with
all three factions in the Bosnian conflict on a cessation of hostilities and
the demilitarisation of the Bosnian capital, Sarajevo.
As fighting continued in Bosnia yesterday, Belgrade Radio said Croat forces
were massing north of Brcko, in the north-east, in an attempt to cut the
Serb-held supply line linking Serbia and Serb-controlled territories.
Croatian radio said Serb forces had launched an offensive on Maglaj, south
of the land corridor.
</TEXT>
