<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Lord Forte hands over to his son but keeps board role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD FORTE, the Italian immigrant and former milk bar proprietor who
established Britain's leading hotel company, announced his retirement as
chairman of Forte yesterday.
He will be succeeded by Mr Rocco Forte, his 47-year-old son, who will add
the title of chairman to the role of chief executive he has held since 1983.
As one of the most notable figures in Britain's post-war business history,
Lord Forte will not easily be forgotten - partly because he is not quite
going.
Lord Forte, 84 next month, will become president and continue to serve on
the board. Mr Forte said he would continue to ask his father for advice when
necessary.
The company has appointed two new non-executive directors. Sir Anthony
Tennant, who retires as chairman of Guinness at the end of this year,
becomes deputy chairman. The other new director is Sir Paul Girolami,
chairman of Glaxo Holdings.
The City welcomed the appointment of two respected, independent figures to
the board.
There was widespread disappointment, however, that the company did not bring
in an outsider as either chairman or chief executive, allowing Mr Forte to
take the remaining role.
Mr Paul Slattery, an analyst with stockbroker Kleinwort Benson, said the
group needed to move away from the culture created by Lord Forte. Among the
changes needed, he said, were greater decentralisation and the granting of
more autonomy to hotel managers.
Mr Rocco Forte defended his assumption of the positions of both chairman and
chief executive. Forte is trying to sell its Gardner Merchant contract
catering subsidiary, which would leave it with two large businesses - hotels
and restaurants. Mr Forte said both would be headed by strong managing
directors, so there was no need to have a separate group chief executive.
He said, however, that impending retirements would enable him to make
further board changes. He denied that, with his father remaining as
president, he would not be in control. 'Being chairman, you have a certain
responsibility to the shareholders. The buck stops with me now, doesn't it?'
