indicated base rates would stay at 9 per cent this month when it offered to
lend money to the market at established rates under a 26-day 'repurchase
agreement'.
Sterling lost two pfennigs against the D-Mark yesterday, closing in London
at DM2.50, after the Bundesbank's monthly report suggested Germany was
unlikely to cut its official rates today. In late New York trading it was
quoted at DM2.4952. UK shares eased on fading hopes of a quick rate cut, and
the FT-SE 100 index closed 10 lower at 2,574.7.
