<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / International Company News: General Electric reports advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Electric, the diversified US holding company, reported a 6.5 per
cent increase in third-quarter net income, with strong growth in businesses
such as financial services and aerospace outweighing lower profits in white
goods and power systems and losses at its NBC broadcasting subsidiary.
The group reported net earnings of Dollars 1.11bn, or Dollars 1.30 a share,
compared with Dollars 1.04bn, or Dollars 1.20, in the third quarter of last
year. Revenues rose from Dollars 14.6bn to Dollars 15.5bn.
Mr Jack Welch, chairman, said GE's productivity growth had continued at an
annual rate of about 5 per cent and he was confident of another year of
record earnings.
However, the operating margin declined from 9.6 per cent a year ago to 9.1
per cent. This was more than accounted for by two unusual factors - higher
restructuring charges and the 1992 Olympic Games, which NBC lost money
covering.
The figures included a gain from a realignment of the equity positions of GE
and Ericsson in their mobile communications venture, which was more than
offset by restructuring charges.
GE's financial services businesses produced net earnings up by 17 per cent.
GE Capital saw double-digit earnings growth, led by commercial equipment
financing and private label credit cards. Kidder Peabody, its securities
house, achieved 'sharply improved 1992 results'.
Aerospace had a 'good increase' in operating profit on higher revenues,
mainly due to sales timing, product mix and productivity gains.
Aircraft engines had flat operating profits, with productivity gains
offsetting a weakness in spare part sales and falling military engine
shipments.
For the nine months, GE made Dollars 3.38bn, up from Dollars 3.17bn, before
the effects of a one-time accounting change taken in the first quarter.
</TEXT>
