<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 92 / Group to be voice for private investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN, Personal Finance Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROSHARE, an organisation which aims to encourage wider share ownership,
launched an association for private investors yesterday, with an
introductory offer of a free half-hour consultation with a stockbroker.
The annual subscription is Pounds 30 and the association aims to provide
investors with independent information and to act as a mouthpiece for
private shareholders.
The number of private investors in the UK was about 3m when the
Conservatives came into office in 1979. It is now about 10m, much of it in
the form of small holdings in privatised stocks. The proportion of the
market owned by private investors is less than 20 per cent, compared with
nearly 70 per cent in 1957.
ProShare argues that a combination of investor ignorance, tax disadvantages
and a shortage of good-quality advice has been a barrier to wider share
ownership. The organisation has received funding of more than Pounds 3m from
the Department of Trade and Industry, the Stock Exchange and leading
companies. It hopes to become self-financing.
Members of the association will receive a handbook, a monthly newsletter and
a voucher for eight free copies of the Saturday edition of the Financial
Times.
More information available on 071-971 0061.
</TEXT>
