<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / C&amp;J Clark compromise planned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DIRECTORS at C&amp;J Clark were last night working on a compromise agreement to
end the two-month-long row at Britain's largest shoe manufacturer.
The compromise could come in time to avert the extraordinary general meeting
called by four board members to unseat Clark chairman Mr Walter Dickson.
A 10-point proposal was put forward by the rebel directors yesterday
afternoon which would leave Mr Dickson and non-executive director Mr James
Power in position.
If agreement is reached, the EGM is likely - at the very least - to be
postponed until the annual meeting in April.
Solicitors and directors were working to reach a compromise by this evening
 -the latest the company could warn its 4,000 shareholders around the UK
that the EGM had been cancelled.
The compromise proposed by the requisitionists - so named for calling the
EGM - made postponement of the meeting conditional on several points. These
are believed to include the formation of an independent bid committee,
chaired by an executive other than Mr Dickson, to review any future offer
for Clark. The condition was made in light of the talks over a possible bid
by management consultant Mr Colin Fisher backed by Electra Investment Trust,
who said Mr Dickson and Mr Power would remain if a bid succeeded.
The requisitionists are also believed to have set out conditions for the
conduct of any future dispute between directors of the company.
The row has thrown Clark, based in Street, Somerset, and controlled by an
extended Quaker family, into the glare of publicity. Both sides have hired
advisers for the dispute, incurring heavy costs in a company with falling
profits. In August, the chairman warned that pre-tax profits would be lower
than last year's Pounds 20.4m and the interim dividend was cut from 3.5p to
1.75p.
The proposals are also believed to include a suggestion to devolve power
within the board. One of the areas of friction has been the increasing
influence of non-family members on the board. Mr Dickson is only the second
non-family member to chair the 167-year-old firm.
</TEXT>
