FT  14 OCT 92 / International Company News: Alcan turns in loss amid
depressed prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALCAN Aluminium reported a loss of USDollars 14m, or 6 cents a share, in the
third quarter because of depressed ingot and fabricated products prices.
A year earlier Alcan just about broke even after a 14 cents a share
provision for restructuring charges.
Until the persistent oversupply in primary metal is corrected, said Mr David
Morton, chairman, 'there is not much room for any near-term improvement in
prices'.
The spot price for primary aluminium yesterday equalled about 52.7 US cents
per lb or below Alcan's breakeven point. The price has fallen steadily from
a summer peak of about 60 US cents.
Third quarter revenues were USDollars 1.97bn, about unchanged from a year
earlier.
For the first nine months, Alcan's loss was USDollars 63m or 28 cents a
share, against a loss of USDollars 15m, or 7 cents, a year earlier, on
revenues of USDollars 5.8bn against USDollars 5.97bn.
Fabricated products were 66 per cent of total third-quarter volume, up from
62 per cent a year earlier. Ingot shipments were lower. However Alcan was on
target with cost-cutting at its primary smelters. Ingot production costs
were USDollars 100 a tonne lower, year on year.
</TEXT>
