</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SHAREHOLDERS of Pohang Iron and Steel (Posco), the South Korean steelmaker,
yesterday approved a proposal to allow foreigners to acquire up to 8 per
cent of the state-affiliated company.
Individual foreign investors will not be allowed to have a shareholding of
more than 1 per cent under the amended by-law, which takes effect today. The
Korean government, which controls 35 per cent of Posco, opened the company
to foreign investment to try to revive the country's stock market by
attracting more capital from abroad.
The extraordinary shareholders' meeting also approved the appointment of Mr
Hwang Kyung-ro, the vice-chairman, as Posco's chairman. He replaces Mr Park
Tae-joon, who resigned last week for political reasons and becomes honorary
chairman.
Mr Chung Myung-sik, Posco president, is the new vice-chairman, while Mr Park
Tuk-pyo, vice-president for strategic planning, becomes president.
Mr Hwang said his goal was to make Posco the world's biggest steelmaker by
1996.
