FT  14 OCT 92 / International Company News: Maybelline may make flotation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MAYBELLINE, the US cosmetics company which was acquired two years ago by
Wasserstein Perella, the New York-based investment banking business, may be
coming to the stock market.
The company, based in Memphis, Tennessee, yesterday filed a registration
statement for 3.145m common shares with the US Securities and Exchange
Commission - a move which, by a privately-owned company, usually presages a
flotation.
According to the filing, the company estimates that the net proceeds of the
offering would be around Dollars 65m, and would be used to prepay a portion
of the a term loan outstanding under the company's bank credit agreement.
Merrill Lynch and Wasserstein Perella Securities are underwriters for the
potential offering, and have an option to purchase another 555,000 shares to
over-allotments.
However, Mr Robert Hiatt, Maybelline's president and chief executive, last
night declined to be drawn on the timing of the potential initial public
offering (the US term for a flotation).
Maybelline was bought by Wasserstein's Dollars 1.1bn merchant banking fund
in 1990 from Schering-Plough, the large drugs group. It has been one of the
most successful constituents of the fund, which is dominated by a 40 per
cent stake in Isosceles, the troubled British food retailer.
Wasserstein paid around Dollars 300m for the cosmetics business, after an
earlier deal with MBP Acquisition Corp, a consortium which included Playtex
Family Products, fell through. At the time, Maybelline was making operating
profits of around Dollars 30m on sales of approximately Dollars 300m.
