FT  14 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Russians buy E German plant
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE COLITT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A former east German state cellulose factory has been sold to a private
Russian company which wants to pay for urgently needed modernisation by
exporting Russian coal to the west, writes Leslie Colitt in Berlin.
Mr Yuri Gekht, chairman of Sokolniki company, signed a contract this week
with the Treuhand privatisation agency to buy the United Cellulose Works in
Pirna which was in liquidation. He paid a symbolic DM1 for the company. Mr
Gekht is a member of the Russian parliament and head of the Producers'
Association.
Sokolniki owns a paper factory in Serpuchov near Moscow and a printing plant
near Tula. It has a licence from the Russian government to produce bonds and
other financial certificates; it needs a steady supply of high-quality
cellulose to assure the quality of its special paper.
