   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Department of Justice is investigating Mr William Sessions, director
of the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), and his wife for the possible
violation of ethics rules, writes Alan Friedman in New York.
The probe of Mr Sessions comes just three days after the Justice Department
called in the FBI to investigate whether Central Intelligence Agency or
Justice officials deliberately concealed intelligence reports relating to
the scandal over Dollars 5bn (Pounds 2.8bn) of illegal loans made to Iraq by
the Atlanta branch of Italy's Banca Nazionale del Lavoro (BNL).
The investigation of Mr Sessions and his wife - concerning allegations made
in anonymous letters that they misused government cars and aircraft and that
Mrs Sessions misused her FBI building pass - triggered suggestions by
Democrats that the probe may be a politically inspired attempt to intimidate
the FBI.
Mr Paul McNulty, a Justice Department spokesman, yesterday denied these
suggestions, which came from congressional investigators. 'That is utter
nonsense. There is no tension between us,' he said.
