<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Stockdale witnesses verbal ping-pong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Vice-President Dan Quayle and Senator Al Gore engaged in some heated
exchanges last night in the only vice-presidential debate of the election
campaign, which culminates on November 3.
Mr Quayle, in a finger-pointing, aggressive mode, accused Mr Gore of
environmental extremism and a tendency to weakness on national security. But
mostly he was intent to charge that Governor Bill Clinton, the Democratic
presidential candidate, was someone who could not tell the truth.
Mr Gore, more even-tempered but unwilling to let Mr Quayle change the
subject, mostly stuck to the Democratic script of emphasising economic
issues. But he also said the Republican campaign had now been taken over by
right-wing extremists out of touch with the interests of real Americans.
Retired Admiral James Stockdale, running mate to Mr Ross Perot, the
independent candidate, often seemed overawed by the occasion and completely
lost the thread of his prepared opening statement. Some of his short
responses verged on inarticulation. On one issue, health care, he confessed
he was 'out of ammunition' and had nothing more to say.
But he managed one telling early intervention, observing after one
particularly sharp verbal volley between Mr Quayle and Mr Gore: 'I think
America is seeing right now why the nation is in gridlock.'
He said at another point: 'I feel like an observer at a ping-pong game'.
To the extent that Mr Stockdale expressed his opinions, his conservative
sympathies were evident, especially on the environment and defence, though
not on abortion. This stands in contrast with Mr Perot, who is usually more
critical of President George Bush than Mr Clinton.
Mr Quayle repeatedly accused Mr Gore of 'pulling a Clinton,' by which he
meant not telling the truth. This, he said, disqualified Mr Clinton from
earning the trust of world leaders. He said that, as vice-president, he had
been tested by fire.
One of Mr Gore's better moments was when he seemed to catch Mr Quayle out on
his knowledge of nuclear disarmament agreements with Russia. He also
probably scored good political points with his arguments that concern for
the environment 'can create jobs' as it was doing in countries such as
Germany and Japan.
Vice-presidential debates are rarely influential in the winning of the White
House and the initial reading of last night's confrontation was that this
would be no exception. Neither Mr Quayle nor Mr Gore landed the telling blow
inflicted on Mr Quayle by Senator Lloyd Bentsen for the Democrats in their
confrontation four years ago.
As the running mate of the front-runner, Mr Gore probably had the most to
lose and the often-derided Mr Quayle the most to gain. Neither disappointed
their supporters.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
