<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 92 / Rise in university student numbers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EVIDENCE of the growing pressure of increased student numbers on
universities comes with the publication today of the latest management
statistics from the Committee of Vice-Chancellors and Principals and the
Universities Funding Council, John Willman writes.
The ratio of students to staff rose to 11.89 in 1990-91, almost 19 per cent
higher than in 1984. The ratio varies considerably between subjects, ranging
from an average of 9.4 in physics to 19.4 in accountancy.
The figures cover the 52 'old' universities in the UK, excluding
polytechnics that became universities this year.
The proportion of university income that comes from student fees has
increased from 9 per cent in 1989-90 to 16 per cent in 1990-91, while the
direct grant from government has fallen from 48 per cent to 39 per cent.
University Management Statistics. Universities Statistical Record, PO Box
130, Cheltenham GL50 3SE. Pounds 20.
</TEXT>
