FT  14 OCT 92 / PM urged to clarify Jubilee Line plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CANARY WHARF'S administrators yesterday wrote to Mr John Major, the prime
minister, urging him to clarify government policy on the planned extension
to the Jubilee Line and the relocation of civil servants to the financially
troubled east London property development.
The administrators - three partners of Ernst &amp; Young, the accountancy firm -
reiterated that Canary Wharf's banks are keen to make a financial
contribution to the Pounds 1.6bn costs of building the Underground
extension.
They want Mr Major to arbitrate in a dispute between government departments
about whether civil servants should move to Canary Wharf and whether the
line should be built.
On Monday evening, the administrators were told by Lord Wakeham - leader of
the House of Lords, who is in charge of a special government Docklands
committee - that more than 2,000 Department of Environment officials are
unlikely to move to Canary Wharf, confounding earlier expectations.
However, Lord Wakeham left open the possibility that officials from other
departments would move to Docklands.
'We have written to the prime minister to ensure that our message gets
across to interested parties,' the administrators said. 'It is not a panic
measure.'
Canary Wharf's bankers fear that the government will abandon the Jubilee
Line project - which would have a detrimental effect on the value of the
development.
The banks' existing offer of Pounds 390m towards the Jubilee Line costs is
conditional on civil servants being moved to Canary Wharf.
</TEXT>
